A Kubernetes namespace is a virtual cluster inside your physical cluster that provides resource isolation and organization. Your K8S_MONITORING_NAMESPACE ?= monitoring groups all monitoring resources (Prometheus, Grafana, ServiceMonitors) together so they don't clash with your app resources.

What namespaces do
Namespaces create scope for namespaced resources like Deployments, Services, Pods, Secrets, and ConfigMaps. Names must be unique within a namespace, but you can reuse names across namespaces.

text
# These can coexist:
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: myapp          # OK in 'default' namespace
  namespace: default
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: myapp          # OK in 'monitoring' namespace  
  namespace: monitoring

Cluster-wide resources (CRDs, Nodes, PersistentVolumes, StorageClasses) ignore namespaces and exist globally.

Key use cases
Use Case	                    Why Namespace Helps
Multi-team clusters	            Team A deploys myapp in team-a, Team B deploys myapp in team-b 
Environment separation	        myapp-dev, myapp-staging, myapp-prod coexist 
Monitoring isolation	        Prometheus/Grafana in monitoring, apps in default 
Resource quotas	Limit           CPU/memory per namespace for cost control 
RBAC scoping	                Users see/manage only their namespace 

You’re already doing PSA correctly for monitoring. To implement the “explicit app namespaces” approach, you’ll:

    - Add namespaces for myapp-dev, myapp-staging, myapp-prod with PSA labels.

    - Add NetworkPolicies in those namespaces that only allow Prometheus (in monitoring) to hit /metrics.